<section><title> Equilibrium Solutions </title>
	<introduction>
		<p>
			Autonomous equations tell us that the direction of change depends only on the current state‚Äînot the current time. That idea shows up clearly in slope fields, where each horizontal line has the same slope behavior. Now we'll zoom in on one especially important feature of these equations: the horizontal lines where the slope is zero. These are the points where the system stands still. They're called <term>equilibrium solutions</term>.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<paragraphs><title> Flat Lines and Fixed Behavior </title>

		<p>
			Let's revisit a slope field, this time for the equation
			<me>
				\frac{dy}{dt} = 1 - y^2.
			</me>
			This is an autonomous equation, so the slope depends only on <m>y</m>. And at certain <m>y</m>-values, something special happens: the slope is exactly zero.
		</p>

		<sidebyside widths="50%" margin="10%" valign="middle">
			<figure xml:id="slope-field-1-ysqrd">
				<image width="50%">
					<latex-image>
						\begin{tikzpicture}[declare function={f(\x,\y) = 1 - \y*\y;}, scale=0.8]

							\pgfkeys{/pgf/number format/.cd,
								fixed,
								precision=1
							}
							\def\tmin{-2.2} \def\tmax{2.2}
							\def\ymin{-2.2} \def\ymax{2.2}
							\def\tstep{0.2}  \def\ystep{0.2}
							\def\arrowscale{0.17} % length of slope arrows
							\def\segmentwt{0.8pt} % thickness of slope segments

							% stepsize along t-axis and y-axis
							\pgfmathsetmacro{\tL}{\tmin + \tstep}
							\pgfmathsetmacro{\tR}{\tmax - \tstep}
							\pgfmathsetmacro{\yL}{\ymin + \ystep}
							\pgfmathsetmacro{\yR}{\ymax - \ystep}
							\pgfmathsetmacro{\nt}{(\tR-\tL)/\tstep}
							\pgfmathsetmacro{\ny}{(\yR-\yL)/\ystep}

							% Axes
							\draw[->] (\tmin, 0) -- (\tmax+0.3, 0) node[xshift=-0.1cm, font=\tiny, below] {$t$};
							\draw[->] (0, \ymin) -- (0, \ymax+0.3) node[yshift=-0.1cm, font=\tiny, left] {$y$};

							% Bounding box
							\draw[gray!50] (\tmin,\ymin) rectangle (\tmax,\ymax);

							% Tick marks and labels on t-axis
							\pgfmathtruncatemacro{\tLint}{\tL}
							\pgfmathtruncatemacro{\tRint}{\tR}
							\foreach \t in {\tLint,...,\tRint} {
								\pgfmathparse{\t &lt; 0}
								\ifnum\pgfmathresult=1	 % shift negative ticks
									\draw (\t,\ymin-0.06) -- (\t,\ymin+0.06)
									node[font=\tiny, below, xshift=-0.01cm] {\t};
								\else
									\draw (\t,\ymin-0.06) -- (\t,\ymin+0.06)
									node[font=\tiny, below] {\t};
								\fi
							}

							% Tick marks and labels on y-axis
							\pgfmathtruncatemacro{\yLint}{\yL}
							\pgfmathtruncatemacro{\yRint}{\yR}
							\foreach \y in {\yLint,...,\yRint}
								\draw (\tmin-0.06,\y) -- (\tmin+0.1,\y)
								node[font=\tiny, left] {\y};

							% slope field: just draw a vector at each point
							\foreach \i in {0,...,\nt}
							\foreach \j in {0,...,\ny}{

								\pgfmathsetmacro{\tpt}{\tL + \i * \tstep}
								\pgfmathsetmacro{\ypt}{\yL + \j * \ystep}
								\pgfmathsetmacro{\slope}{f(\tpt,\ypt)}

								% Normalize direction vector (1, slope) to fixed length
								\pgfmathsetmacro{\len}{sqrt(1 + (\slope)^2)}
								\pgfmathsetmacro{\dt}{\arrowscale / \len}
								\pgfmathsetmacro{\dy}{\arrowscale * \slope / \len}

								\draw[teal!75, line width=\segmentwt, shift={(\tpt,\ypt)}] (-0.5*\dt, -0.5*\dy) -- (0.5*\dt, 0.5*\dy);
								%\draw[fill=white!50] (\tpt,\ypt) circle (1.5pt);
							}

						\end{tikzpicture}
					</latex-image>
				</image>
				<caption>Slope field for <m>y' = 1 - y^2</m></caption>
			</figure>
		</sidebyside>

		<p>
			In the slope field, these show up as rows of perfectly horizontal segments. That's no accident‚Äîat these <m>y</m>-values, the derivative <m>dy/dt</m> is zero, so the solution doesn't move at all. If a solution curve starts at one of these values, it stays there forever. These flat lines are what we call <term>equilibrium solutions</term>.
		</p>

		<p>
			You can find them by solving the equation
			<me>
				f(y) = 0,
			</me>
			where <m>f(y)</m> is the right-hand side of the differential equation. In this case:
			<me>
				1 - y^2 = 0 \quad\Rightarrow\quad y = -1 \quad \text{or} \quad y = 1.
			</me>
			So the equilibrium solutions are the constant functions <m>y(t) = -1</m> and <m>y(t) = 1</m>.
		</p>

		<p>
			These constant solutions are part of the larger family of solutions to the differential equation. But they're important because they act like anchors: other solutions either drift toward them or away from them. We'll explore that behavior more in the next section.
		</p>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs><title> What the Slope Field Tells You </title>

		<p>
			What happens at <em>other</em> values of <m>y</m>? Well, between the equilibria at <m>y = -1</m> and <m>y = 1</m>, we can plug in a number like <m>y = -0.5</m>. Then:
			<me>
				f(-0.5) = 1 - (-0.5)^2 = 1 - 0.25 = 0.75,
			</me>
			so the slope is positive and the solution increases. The slope field confirms this‚Äîbetween the equilibrium lines, the segments tilt upward.
		</p>

		<p>
			Above <m>y = 1</m>, try <m>y = 1.5</m>:
			<me>
				f(1.5) = 1 - (1.5)^2 = -1.25,
			</me>
			which is negative, so solutions decrease. And again, the slope field shows those segments tilting downward. The same thing happens below <m>y = -1</m>.
		</p>

		<p>
			These slope patterns give you a kind of ‚Äúbehavior map.‚Äù Equilibrium solutions mark the places where nothing changes. And everywhere else, the slope field shows which direction nearby solutions are pulled‚Äîor pushed.
		</p>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs><title> How to Find Equilibrium Solutions </title>

		<p>
			Finding equilibrium solutions for an autonomous differential equation is always the same process:
		</p>

		<ol>
			<li>Start with the equation <m>\frac{dy}{dt} = f(y)</m>.</li>
			<li>Set <m>f(y) = 0</m>.</li>
			<li>Solve for the constant values <m>y = c</m> that make this true.</li>
			<li>Each solution <m>y(t) = c</m> is an equilibrium solution.</li>
		</ol>

		<p>
			Let's do a quick example. Consider:
			<me>
				\frac{dy}{dt} = y^2 - 4y.
			</me>
			Set the right-hand side to zero:
			<me>
				y^2 - 4y = 0 \quad\Rightarrow\quad y(y - 4) = 0.
			</me>
			The equilibrium solutions are:
			<me>
				y(t) = 0 \quad \text{and} \quad y(t) = 4.
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			Once you have these, you can sketch horizontal lines at those values of <m>y</m> in the slope field. Then examine how the slope segments behave above and below each line‚Äîthat will help you understand how the other solutions evolve, and whether they're drawn toward or repelled from the equilibrium.
		</p>
	</paragraphs>

